The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Shoppers Stop off to a flying start

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT 

 Mumbai, May 23: Shoppers Stop had a grand debut on the bourses today. On the BSE, the stock opened at Rs 335.50, a premium of 41 per cent on its offer price, and ended the day higher at Rs 372.60, a premium of 56 per cent.

 The scrip remained firm throughout the day and shot up to an intra-day high of Rs 419.80. 

 The top traded counter in the B1 group, Shoppers Stop witnessed 38,921 trades with over 42 lakh shares being transacted. This resulted in a turnover of Rs 164.15 crore.

 We want to create a world-class organisation and are focussed on making Shoppers Stop the countrys number one retail chain. As part of our growth plans, we unveiled two new stores. We will work tirelessly towards creating value for our existing as well as new investors, which totals more than 56000, B. S. Nagesh, CEO and managing director of Shoppers Stop, said.

 The successful listing of Shoppers Stop also saw investors chasing its peers with both Pantaloon Retail and Trent closing on higher ground. Pantaloon Retail, which opened at Rs 1,100, closed at Rs 1,111.25 compared with its last close of Rs 1070.55. 

 Similarly, Trent started on a strong note at Rs 613, rose to an intra-day high of Rs 627.90 before closing at Rs 612.60.

 Shoppers Stop had entered the capital market with its maiden public offering of 6,946,033 shares of Rs10 each in a price band of Rs 210 and Rs 250 per share. The issue opened for bids on April 28 and closed on May 4. Funds raised will be used to finance 11 new stores apart from renovating existing stores. 




